BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:bXYXQWAhSjp-k-54LADmy
SUMMARY:Eric-Paul Riege: ojo|-|ólǫ́
DTSTAMP:20260411T040902Z
DTSTART:20260424T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:ojo|-|ólǫ́ is an exhibition of recent and newly commissioned w
	ork by Diné artist Eric-Paul Riege \\(b. 1994\, Na’nízhoozhí \\[Gallup\, N
	ew Mexico\\]\\) that includes sculpture\, textile\, collage\, and video\, 
	activated by moments of performance. Across this work\, Riege combines cus
	tomary Diné practices of weaving\, silversmithing\, and beading with conte
	mporary cultural forms\, exploring Diné cosmology\, the history of Euro-Am
	erican trading posts in and adjacent to the Navajo Nation\, and the notion
	 of “authenticity” as a value marker of Indigenous art and craft.\n\nDevel
	oped in partnership between the Henry and The Bell Gallery at Brown Univer
	sity\, ojo|-|ólǫ́ emerged from Riege’s material research with Navajo coll
	ections housed at Brown’s Haffenreffer Museum of Anthropology and the Univ
	ersity of Washington’s Burke Museum of Natural History and Culture. The re
	sulting body of work celebrates the ancestral knowledge and labor containe
	d within Indigenous-made objects\, while investigating the role of museums
	 and other institutions in the dissemination and dispossession of knowledg
	e about Indigenous cultures. For his tactile and modular soft sculptures\,
	 Riege employs exaggerated scale and combines synthetic and natural materi
	als to playfully question ideas of authenticity and Indigenous artistic pr
	oduction. Processes of making and remaking embody a living practice of exc
	hange that draws together webs of connection across time and space.\n\nThe
	 exhibition also includes objects from the Burke collection displayed alon
	gside assorted ephemera from Riege’s own home and studio. The resulting no
	n-hierarchal display blurs lines between past and present\, private and pu
	blic\, and real and fake\, animating the dynamism and dimensionality of In
	digenous cultures and identities. ojo|-|ólǫ́ invites collective reflection
	 on the practices of institutions that have accumulated Indigenous art\, w
	hile advancing a call for Indigenous cultural resurgence in the present an
	d toward our shared future.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/detai
	ls/eric-paul-riege-ojo-o-l/18307676/2026-04-24T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts 
	& Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/eric-paul-riege-ojo-o-l/1
	8307676/2026-04-24T00
LOCATION:Henry Art Gallery\, 15th Ave NE & 41st St\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:r1XCah_qwT03IHQdzJAfu
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260411T040902Z
DTSTART:20260424T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-04-24T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-04-24T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:bpo9roVtrnSiee4Gim6o8
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260411T040902Z
DTSTART:20260424T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-24T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-24T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:6OXXkPPGrbq42gXJI3wxX
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260411T040902Z
DTSTART:20260424T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	4-24T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-04-24T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:baWvzGwBLyLZZS4T7TL1q
SUMMARY:You've Had It In You All Along
DTSTAMP:20260411T040902Z
DTSTART:20260424T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Artists: Barbara Earl Thomas | Tariqa Waters | Cristina Martine
	z | Robert Wade | Maikoiyo Alley-Barnes | Nahom Ghirmay “\n\nYou’ve Had It
	 In You All Along” is an affirmation of our capability to weather any stor
	m. It serves as a vital reminder that the tools required to reach your des
	tination are already etched within your spirit. We already carry the brill
	iance and the beauty of what it takes—the confidence\, the strength\, the 
	security\, the poise\, and the knowledge to achieve our goals. The grit\, 
	the rigor\, the radical ideas\, and the voice required to transcend the wo
	rld around us are not external gifts to be acquired\; they are inherent po
	wers waiting for the moment of their activation. \n\nIn the process of ove
	rcoming—when the pathway forward is unclear and the effort feels endless—i
	t is easy to lose sight of our own internal compass. When we stand face-to
	-face with rejection\, heartbreak\, or the heavy weight of difficult seaso
	ns\, this exhibition serves as a sanctuary to remind us that we have alway
	s been more than enough\, exactly as we are. Breakthroughs happen in the s
	pace where we are gentle with ourselves\, allowing for the activation of a
	n inner wisdom and intuition that has been present since our first breath.
	\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/you-ve-had-it-in-you-all
	-along/18494682/2026-04-24T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/you-ve-had-it-in-you-all-
	along/18494682/2026-04-24T00
LOCATION:Avery Barnes Gallery\, 120 First Ave. S.\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:Tub5NnLZRgp0uufZyUM3v
SUMMARY:Decay
DTSTAMP:20260411T040902Z
DTSTART:20260424T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:Decay explores how we navigate and engage with the inevitable e
	ntropy of our world.\n\nThis exhibition shows us the joy of degeneration\,
	 the beauty of collapse\, the peace that comes from crumbling into dust. T
	he work\, primarily from Pacific Northwest artists\, ranges from sculptura
	l\, to wall-mounted 3D\, video and installation works. Included in this ex
	hibition will be works created using natural and reclaimed materials\, as 
	well as pieces designed to create spaces for quiet reflection on the theme
	. Decay appears as part of the natural world and in our bodies in many for
	ms\, and so over the duration of the show\, some works may change over tim
	e\, exemplifying the theme. Many of the pieces prompt reflection on mortal
	ity\, the fragility of the physical body and the sacred.\n\nhttps://seatod
	ay.6amcity.com/events/#/details/decay/18493748/2026-04-24T00\n\nFrom SEAto
	day - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/decay/18493748/2026-04-24
	T00
LOCATION:The Vestibule\, 5919 15th Ave. N.W.\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT5H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:TxpYr3SswlNA_tvn1wnI3
SUMMARY:Scott Gibson - Visual Symphony II
DTSTAMP:20260411T040902Z
DTSTART:20260424T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:In March\, Visual Symphony II Scott Gibson invites viewers into
	 a world where music and art collide. Each work is an exploration of the v
	ivid\, sensory experience of sound translating into vibrant\, emotional vi
	suals. As an artist with synesthesia each work expresses Scott’s personal 
	perception of what music looks like. Scott uses resin techniques that he h
	as pioneered and pushes the boundaries of this medium.\n\nhttps://seatoday
	.6amcity.com/events/#/details/scott-gibson-visual-symphony-ii/18280602/202
	6-04-24T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
